metrics_conclusion: drowning has higher complexity than the average song  in terms Chord-Melody Tension and Chord-Bass Melody.
key_conclusion:
drowning is written in the key of E Minor.  

According to the Theorytab database, it is the 2nd most popular key among Minor keys and     the 8th most popular  among all keys. Minor keys, along with major keys, are a common choice for popular music.  The three most important chords, built off the 1st, 4th and 5th scale degrees are all minor chords (E minor, A minor, and B minor).

See the E Minor Cheat Sheet for popular chords, chord progressions, downloadable midi files and more!

metadata.editComments: Added the second half of the intro. Also, it's worth nothing that the chord progression from Em, D, C chord progression acts as a motif between both Drowning and Fumes.
Technically this is just the second half of the intro, but I needed to make a new section since the tempo changes halfway through.

The two verses don't use the exact same chords. This first verse uses a G chord from some guitar ambiance between the main C to Em loop. The second verses throws in a D chord, different rests, and borrows the chorus chord progression towards the end. I'll likely upload the second verse separately.
Fixed the melody and notated the entire first chorus.

The motif from the beginning of the song makes an appearance again here.

My transcription of the melody isn't quite exact since EDEN's singing wasn't totally on rhythm. I tried syncing it as close as i could.
